history.content:
They are all good classes that you should take if you have room in your schedule.  Math 110 tackles much harder theoretical topics than EE16A or B.   EE16A is almost identical to 2/3 of Math 54, and parts of EE16B fill in the differential equations knowledge.  EE16B's main extra linear algebra topic is singular value decomposition.

Because you do need to take EE16 classes as a graduation requirement, assuming you are CS, I think you would have to go with those.  Another option you could do is to take EECS 47D (circuits part of 16A), and then EE16B. Then you could also take Math 110 at some point.  

Alternatively, if you do get around to CS189 or EE127 you also tend to pick up on some linear algebra skills.

children.subject: Following up, I'd say EE16A and EE16B roughly covers MATH 54 in linear algebra topics.  But not MATH 110.
